intellectus&rdquo;, discussed in <em>Corpus iconographicum. Le
incisioni nelle opere a stampa</em>, ed. M. Gabriele (Milan, 2001)
374&ndash;379; and reconstructed by Raymond Kotty at
 <a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=rAw8thcZsgU" target="other">https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=rAw8thcZsgU</a>
 </p>
</div>

<h2 id="Reli">10. Religion</h2>

<p>
Marsilio Ficino, Giovanni Pico della Mirandola (in one phase of his
career) and other Renaissance authors had held similarly
&ldquo;Pelagian&rdquo; views that philosophy led to self-perfection
and &ldquo;deification&rdquo;. Yet they had stopped well short of
denying the integrity of Christianity. Philosophy and religion were,
so to speak, two parallel paths, suited to different audiences. Bruno
had no such scruples. Philosophy&mdash;Bruno&rsquo;s philosophy of God
as immanent in an infinite universe as announced in <em>The Ash
Wednesday Supper</em>&mdash;was the true bread of life. It
&ldquo;illuminated the blind&rdquo;, &ldquo;loosed the tongue of the
dumb&rdquo;, &ldquo;cured the lame&rdquo;, so that the human spirit
could once again &ldquo;progress&rdquo; (BOI I, 454). Its powers, that
is, were miraculous, Christ-like, salvific. Who deserved praise the
more: someone who healed a worthless cripple, or a man who liberated
his homeland or who reformed, not a mere body, but a mind (BOI II,
264&ndash;267)? In other words, who was the true saviour: Christ or
Bruno? By contrast, Christian practices and ideals were fraudulent
(BOI II, 263&ndash;266, 658). Under a thin veil of irony, all the
while denying the irony, Bruno praised the various guises under which
Christianity taught that ignorance of the natural world led the soul
to God. Among its many deceits were: scriptural injunctions to
acknowledge our ignorance, notably, the Pauline theme of folly; the
ascetic mysticism of pseudo-Dionysius the Areopagite and mystics
generally; claims that the light of faith and revelation were superior
to human knowledge; Augustine&rsquo;s emphasis on the fallen nature of
mankind, particularly the corruption of knowledge innate to it;
injunctions to be childlike and meek; and the humility and obedience
that the Christian clergy sought to instill among its flock (BOI II,
380&ndash;384, 415, 422&ndash;430, 443&ndash;448; BOL I.2, 316). The
philosopher should ignore these &ldquo;foolish dreams&rdquo; (BOL I.3,
200)&mdash;in practical as well as in intellectual endeavours. To be
virtuous was to strive against adversity and to aspire, even if with
only partial or little success (BOI I, 475&ndash;476; II, 568), to an
ever greater understanding of intelligible reality
 (<a href="#Panpsychism">Section 9</a>). The
 unremitting nature of this quest was not the outcome of, so to speak,
a Promethean or Adamic fall from divine favour, but rather
part-and-parcel of the vicissitude characterizing the universe of
things
 (<a href="#CosmUnivAtom">Section 3</a>).
 &ldquo;Where opposites meet, there is order, there resides
virtue&rdquo; (BOI II, 549). Happiness was not so much a goal, in this
or some future life, as the transient state of mind
occurring as we passed from a privation to its opposite. We are
happy when we eat after feeling hungry, when we go out &ldquo;into the
countryside&rdquo; after being confined indoors, and so forth and
so on (BOI, 197&ndash;198). </p>

<p>
Simultaneously, with the same indignation that Spinoza and Nietzsche
would later voice, Bruno impugned the clerical caste. Living
parasitically off the labours of others (BOI II, 238&ndash;239) and
affecting &ldquo;a foul-smelling melancholy&rdquo;, i.e.,
<em>accidia</em> (BOL II.2,189&ndash;190), they advocated the solitary
life and renunciation of this world for the next. Such men had
extinguished the divine light that had made the souls of the ancients
&ldquo;heroic and divine&rdquo; (BOI I, 453). Of all peoples, the
ancient Romans had best understood the value of &ldquo;glory&rdquo;
for establishing and maintaining civilization. A true religion, like
that of the ancients, extolled men of action, strength of body and
mind and worldly glory (BOI II, 267&ndash;268). Similar comments on
clerical duplicity, glory and religion occur in Machiavelli, whose
works Bruno had probably read.</p>

<p>
Nevertheless, religion had a role to play. The &ldquo;uneducated
populace&rdquo; (BOI I, 525; II, 514&ndash;515) could not aspire to
philosophical perfection. They needed laws and sanctions to keep their
conduct in check. Religion, with its promises of reward and punishment
in an afterlife, served this purpose. When Moses had led the
Israelites from captivity, they were no more than an uneducated
rabble. To govern them, he established laws and enforced them with
terrifying accounts of an almighty, wrathful God who administered
retribution in an afterlife. Scripture, whether Jewish, Islamic or
Christian, had been composed with this practical goal in mind (BOI I,
522&ndash;528). Admittedly, Bruno conceded, Scripture did sometimes
record philosophical truths. Genesis and the Book of Job were
conspicuous repositories. This was only to be expected, given that
Scripture was a tributary of &ldquo;the ancient philosophy&rdquo; (see
 <a href="#WisdAnci">Section 2</a>).
 For the most part, however, it simplified. Several passages of
Scripture (e.g., Ecclesiastes, 1:5&ndash;6; Joshua 10:12&ndash;13)
implied that the sun circled the motionless earth. This was a
simplification made for the benefit of the uneducated. Disquisitions
based on a true, heliocentric, interpretation of celestial motion
would have, at best, confused them and, at worst, led them,
counterproductively, to dismiss Scripture&rsquo;s tales of divine
retribution (BOI I, 522&ndash;525).</p>

<p>
To claim that Scripture made allowances for the weak understanding of
most men and women was nothing new. Patristic, Catholic and Protestant
theologians acknowledged that Moses had addressed an ignorant, slavish
people and that Scripture spoke in a way that the uneducated could
understand. All agreed, too, that it focused on moral and spiritual
issues and refrained from intricate philosophical arguments.
Bruno&rsquo;s appeal to these positions disguised his heterodoxy. The
crucial deviation was his denial of miracles, the most important of
all testimonies to the Christian faith. Given that the laws of nature
were, essentially, &ldquo;God in things&rdquo;, they were
&ldquo;inviolable&rdquo; (BOL I.2, 316). In this respect, he went far
beyond the Paduan natural philosopher Pietro Pomponazzi
(1462&ndash;1525), who, disposed though he was to attribute miraculous
events, Scriptural or otherwise, to natural causation, allowed that
some were authentic. Repeatedly Bruno mocked, allusively, the miracles
reported in the Old and New Testament, including those performed by
Moses and Christ (BOI II, 380&ndash;381; BOL III, 397; Firpo 2000,
277&ndash;279, &sect;51.41&ndash;42). Christ&rsquo;s were
<em>bagatelle</em>, &ldquo;sleights of hand&rdquo; (BOI II, 383). They
were no more than &ldquo;natural magic&rdquo; (BOL II.2, 73, 199),
effects produced by manipulating &ldquo;occult&rdquo;, that is,
natural, though imperceptible, forces (BOL II.1, 348, citing II.2,
180&ndash;193). Or, indeed, they may have been the fruits of demonic
magic, a comment which implied that Christ had commerce with demons.
Christ began to perform miracles, Bruno noted, only &ldquo;after his
struggle with the devil in the desert&rdquo; (BOL II.2, 181). The
allusive style in which Bruno disguised his views only served to
accentuate his blasphemies, mixing as they did ridicule and contempt
with heresy. Handwritten annotations in copies of his works show that
contemporaries or near contemporaries recognized his intentions easily
enough (Sturlese 1987).</p>

<p>
Philosophers, &ldquo;heroes&rdquo;, did not need Scripture&rsquo;s
bogus threats of retribution and promises of future rewards to cajole
them into behaving morally. They understood the &ldquo;pattern
(<em>istoria</em>) of Nature inscribed within [them]&rdquo; (BOI II,
24&ndash;25), that God, in other words, was with and within them (BOI
I, 455&ndash;456; II, 658&ndash;659), and governed their actions
accordingly. Those who considered the matter carefully, &ldquo;truly
religious men&rdquo;, &ldquo;men who are good by nature&rdquo;, would
see that Bruno&rsquo;s philosophy, more than any other, &ldquo;not
only contains the truth but also favours religion&rdquo; (BOI I, 528).
They did not need rituals involving some &ldquo;food and drink&rdquo;
to revere the divine (BOL I.1, 205; Knox 2020b). On diverse occasions,
he covertly mocked the Eucharist (BOL II.2, 181&ndash;182), despising
as he did the &ldquo;subtleties&rdquo; of scholastic accounts of
transubstantiation (Spampanato 1933, 40). Instead, it was the majesty
of Nature, the infinite animate, panpsychic universe, that inspired
the wonder and reverence of truly divine men and led them to search
for its cause (see
 <a href="#UniverseImageGod">Section 5</a>).
 In so doing they became themselves &ldquo;greater than those gods
whom blind commoners worship&rdquo; (BOI II, 24). Stripped, in short,
of its false claims, Christianity could be seen for what it was, a
&ldquo;foolish faith and blind credulity&rdquo; (BOI II, 386;
similarly, II, 398), &ldquo;a wretched story&rdquo; (BOL I.2, 172),
&ldquo;a worthless, pernicious fable&rdquo; (BOI II, 400), a
continuation of Judaism, a religion invented by that &ldquo;pestilent,
leprous and wholly pernicious&rdquo; race, the Jews (BOI II,
314&ndash;315; for similar stereotypical anti-Jewish comments, see
 <a href="#WisdAnci">Section 2</a>
 and the caveat there regarding the extent to which they reflect
Bruno&rsquo;s views). With its threats that the world would end and
its stories of a God who wrought miracles at whim, it had cowed a
&ldquo;stupefied&rdquo; world into despising Nature&mdash;&ldquo;God
in things&rdquo;&mdash;and, &ldquo;having smashed the tables of
Nature&rdquo; (cf. Exodus, 32:19), looked forward joyfully to the ruin
of all things (BOL I.2, 123).</p>

<p>
Bruno&rsquo;s several clashes with ecclesiastical authorities testify
to his impatience with Christianity of whatever shade. The sectarian
violence that plagued the sixteenth century plainly showed that it had
done the very opposite of what religion should do (BOL II.2, 181).
There are, however, many indications that Bruno found Protestantism
the more irksome variant. Above all Protestants&rsquo; denial of the
efficacy of &ldquo;good works&rdquo; and free will and, conversely,
their emphasis on the inner spirit, predestination and justification
through &ldquo;faith alone&rdquo;, were unconducive to civil order,
political stability and material prosperity. They had purloined the
churches, temples, chapels, hospices, hospitals, colleges and
universities established by the labour of &ldquo;others&rdquo;, that
is, by Catholics, while declaring that &ldquo;their every concern was
with things invisible&rdquo; (BOI II, 238&ndash;239). The latter,
although &ldquo;imperfect and not as good as they should be&rdquo;,
had, unlike their &ldquo;pernicious&rdquo; Protestant counterparts,
promoted the well-being of the state, encouraged philosophical
pursuits and morality, and rewarded well-doers (BOI II, 238). In these
respects, indeed, they were not so different to the ancient Romans
(BOI II, 267). At several points Bruno&rsquo;s turn of phrase suggests
that his ridicule of Protestant theology was directed specifically
against Luther&rsquo;s <em>On the Bondage of the Will</em> (1525) and
that, in formulating his riposte, he drew on Erasmus&rsquo;s <em>On
Free Will</em> (1524), the work that had prompted Luther to write his
treatise in the first place.</p>

<h2 id="BrunAfte">11. Bruno&rsquo;s Afterlife</h2>

<p>
Bruno&rsquo;s philosophy, his views on religion and his execution
earned him notoriety. &ldquo;It is reasonable to denounce
Bruno&rdquo;, wrote the French mathematician, philosopher and
theologian Marin Mersenne (1588&ndash;1648), &ldquo;as one of the most
evil men that the earth has ever borne&rdquo; (Mersenne,
<em>L&rsquo;Impi&eacute;t&eacute; des d&eacute;istes</em>, I.10). What
perturbed Mersenne and many others, including Descartes, was not so
much Bruno&rsquo;s doctrines concerning the earth&rsquo;s mobility,
the elemental homogeneity of the universe, the plurality of worlds and
other cosmological innovations, but rather the underlying doctrine of
the World Soul and its perceived corollaries: pantheism, demonology,
magic, metempsychosis, the claim that God&rsquo;s absolute power
necessitated an infinite product, the essential identity of human,
plant and animal souls, the elimination of individual responsibility,
denial of miracles&mdash;in short, &ldquo;atheism&rdquo; (Ricci
1996).</p>

<p>
Demonizing Bruno lent him, however, a certain fascination. To his
dismay, Mersenne observed that some of his compatriots amused
themselves by reading his <em>On the Cause, the Principle and the
One</em>. During the course of the seventeenth century, Bruno&rsquo;s
ideas continued to appeal to libertines, Rosicrucians and other
unorthodox thinkers, despite, or perhaps because of, the censures of
conventional theologians and philosophers. In his <em>Oculus
sidereus</em> (<em>Starry Gaze</em>), published at Danzig in 1644, the
Rosicrucian Abraham von Franckenberg (1593&ndash;1652), a
disciple of Jacob B&ouml;hme, praised Bruno for &ldquo;his
profound and most thorough investigation into Nature, hidden and
manifest&rdquo;, and included a synopsis, the first to be
printed, of the eight books of his Latin prosimetrum treatise, <em>De
immenso</em> (1591), in which he related its ideas to those of
ancient and Renaissance authors, among them Francesco Zorzi
(1466&ndash;1540), Francesco Patrizi (1529&ndash;1597) and Tommaso
Campanella (1568&ndash;1639). Bruno&rsquo;s space, wrote Franckenberg, was
the Kabbalists&rsquo; &ldquo;God as space&rdquo;, their Ensoph, the
first of the ten Sephiroth (Franckenberg, <em>Oculus sidereus</em>,
&sect;&sect;33&ndash;40; Ricci 1990, 137&ndash;152). In
the Appendix, Franckenberg presented a list of Bruno&rsquo;s
Italian and Latin works and quoted at length five passages from his
so-called <em>Frankfurt trilogy</em>(1591). In England and on
the Continent, John Toland championed Bruno&rsquo;s philosophy,
incurring the disapproval of Leibniz and others. Leibniz&rsquo;s early
enthusiasm for Bruno had dissipated; the striking similarities between
aspects of his monadology and Bruno&rsquo;s doctrine of minims are
probably attributable to the sources and philosophical interests that
they shared in common, rather than direct influence (Brown 2002).
Among the seventeenth-century advocates of heliocentricism, Johannes
Kepler, averse though he was to Bruno&rsquo;s suggestion that the
universe was infinite and his apparent conflation of God and matter,
engaged circumspectly with his cosmological ideas on several
occasions, particularly through the intermediary of the Imperial
Counsellor to Rudolph II, Johannes Matthaeus Wacker von Wackenfels, an
enthusiast of Bruno&rsquo;s cosmology (Ricci 1990, 68&ndash;79;
Granada 2008). In private conversation, Kepler, the newly appointed
Imperial Mathematician, chided Galileo Galilei for not having
acknowledged the contribution that others, including Bruno and
himself, had made to the novelties recorded in his <em>Starry
Messenger</em>, published in 1610 (Hasdale 1610; Ricci 1990, 74n).</p>

<p>
Interest in Bruno&rsquo;s philosophy remained, nevertheless, sporadic.
Copies of his works were hard to come by and, for the most part, the
ideas in them remained curiosities, outlined in encyclopedias and
histories of philosophy, such as those of Pierre Bayle and J. J.
Brucker, with warnings about his extravagant, wayward, genius. More
than any other philosopher, Bruno proved &ldquo;that often the greater
the power of intellect, the less judgement there is&rdquo; (Brucker,
<em>Historia critica philosophiae</em>, IV, pt 2, 30).
&ldquo;Gold&rdquo; there was to be discovered, but it lay concealed
within the &ldquo;dung&rdquo; of his confused thinking (ibid., 31).
What changed Bruno&rsquo;s fortunes decisively was the advent of
&ldquo;Spinozism&rdquo;. The similarities between Bruno&rsquo;s and
Spinoza&rsquo;s substance monism had long been noticed. Bayle, no
admirer of Spinoza, pointed them out, as did Mathurin Veyssi&egrave;re
de Lacroze by way of denigrating Bruno as an &ldquo;atheist&rdquo;
(Veyssi&egrave;re de Lacroz, <em>Entretiens</em>, 284&ndash;325).
Brucker conceded that there were some resemblances but concluded that
Bruno did not merit the charge of &ldquo;Spinozism&rdquo;
(<em>Historia critica philosophiae</em>, IV, pt 2, 52&ndash;54),
arguing that, for Bruno, the universe emanated from, rather than was
identical with, God
 (cf. <a href="#UniverseImageGod">Sections 5&ndash;7</a>).
 Then, in the second half of the eighteenth century Bruno&rsquo;s
fortunes began to change spectacularly. The key moment was the
publication in 1785 of Friedrich Jacobi&rsquo;s
<em>Concerning the Doctrine of Spinoza in Letters to Herr Moses
Mendelssohn</em>, in which Jacobi, without Mendelssohn&rsquo;s
consent, published an exchange of letters between them concerning
Lessing&rsquo;s alleged &ldquo;Spinozism&rdquo; and Spinoza&rsquo;s
philosophy more generally. Jacobi, an opponent of Enlightenment
rationalism, praised Spinoza&rsquo;s philosophy, in the
&ldquo;purified&rdquo; form proposed by some exponents, as an
exemplary manifestation of what pure reason, left to its own devices,
could achieve. Equally, however, it manifested the limitations of
reason, more specifically rational theism. It led essentially to
materialism, fatalism and atheism. In 1789, Jacobi issued an expanded
edition of his work, which included, in a new preface, a brief
discussion of Bruno and his monism (Jacobi, <em>Ueber die Lehre des
Spinoza</em>, VII&ndash;XII)
and, in an appendix, a
German paraphrase of <em>On the Cause, the Principle and the
One, </em>together with an extended quotation from the second
dialogue in the original Italian (Jacobi, <em>Ueber die Lehre des
Spinoza</em>, 261&ndash;307). His purpose in combining Spinoza and Bruno was
to provide &ldquo;a summa of the philosophy of the &#7961;&nu;
&kappa;&alpha;&#8054; &Pi;&#8049;&nu;&rdquo;, a reference to
Lessing&rsquo;s &ldquo;pantheist&rdquo; theology as well as an
allusion to Heraclitus&rsquo;s monism. For all Giordano Bruno&rsquo;s
&ldquo;impenetrability and Heraclitean darkness&rdquo;, it was
difficult to give &ldquo;a purer or better explained outline of
pantheism in the broadest sense&rdquo; (Jacobi, <em>Ueber die
Lehre des Spinoza</em>, <small>IX</small>, <small>XI</small>).
Jacobi&rsquo;s description of Bruno alluded, quite appropriately
given the intricacies of Bruno&rsquo;s philosophy, to the sobriquet
&Sigma;&kappa;&omicron;&tau;&epsilon;&iota;&nu;&#972;&sigmaf;
(&lsquo;Dark&rsquo; or &lsquo;Obscure&rsquo;) by which Heraclitus, on
account of his obscure, riddling, style, had been known in
antiquity and thereafter (e.g. Cicero, <em>On Ends</em>,
II.5.15).</p>

<p>
In the ensuing intellectual uproar, the <em>Pantheismusstreit</em>
(&ldquo;Pantheism controversy&rdquo;) that dominated late eighteenth-
and early nineteenth-century German philosophy, Bruno emerged as the
great precursor of Spinoza and a major philosopher in his own right.
Spinoza and Spinozists had followed in Bruno&rsquo;s footsteps,
concluded F. W. J. Schelling, who wrote a dialogue, <em>Bruno or On
the Divine and Natural Principle of Things</em> (1802), setting out a
Platonized form of Spinozism. Goethe, writing to Schiller, while
expressing reservations, confided that what &ldquo;he understood or
thought he understood&rdquo; of the dialogue was in tune with his
&ldquo;innermost convictions&rdquo; (McFarland 1969, 247). Many others
concurred, among them Hegel, who, in his <em>Lectures on the History
of Philosophy</em>, praised Bruno&rsquo;s writings, fantastic and
confused though they might be, for displaying &ldquo;a sense of
indwelling spirit&rdquo; (pt 2, section 3, &sect;B3). Coleridge was a
steadfast admirer, even in later life, when his philosophical and
religious views were less consonant with Bruno&rsquo;s. &ldquo;This
man&rdquo;, he wrote in 1819, &ldquo;though a pantheist, was
religious&rdquo; (Gatti 2011, 203; Knox 2020b, 43). This new found
enthusiasm led to the publication of editions of Bruno&rsquo;s Italian
and Latin works in Germany by Adolph Wagner (1830) and August
Friedrich Gfr&ouml;rer (1836) respectively, the first editions of his
works in their original languages since the mid-seventeenth
century.</p>

<p>
This European revival was the setting for Bruno&rsquo;s rehabilitation
in Italy. Hegel, Jules Michelet (1798&ndash;1874) and others had portrayed
the period that we now know, thanks to Michelet, as the Renaissance
and Reformation as the birthplace of modernity. This was manifest
above all, though not exclusively, through the artistic, literary and
philosophical achievements of the period, which had broken the Roman
Catholic Church&rsquo;s dominance in spiritual and cultural concerns.
For many, the most conspicuous being Jacob Burckhardt in <em>The
Civilization of the Renaissance in Italy</em> (1860), the honour for
this rupture belonged principally to the Italians, &ldquo;the first
born among the sons of present-day Europe&rdquo; (pt 2, ch. 1).
Sentiments of these kinds were welcome in Italy. Pride in its cultural
achievements fed into the crescendo of nationalist fervour&mdash;the
&ldquo;Risorgimento&rdquo;, leading eventually to the proclamation of
Italy as an independent kingdom in 1861&mdash;and mounting hostility
in some circles towards the Roman Catholic Church. The Church had been
blamed for the peninsula&rsquo;s political fragmentation and
intellectual atrophy ever since the Counter-Reformation.</p>

<p>
Circumstances could scarcely have been more propitious for heterodox
Renaissance thinkers such as Telesio, Tommaso Campanella, Galileo and,
above all, Bruno. For many Italians, his philosophy, heroic defiance
of ecclesiastical authority and execution exemplified the long
struggle to free philosophy from the trammels of revealed religion.
Popular versions of Bruno&rsquo;s life and death likened him to
Socrates, Christ or, nearer home, martyrs of the Risorgimento. This
adulation found its most visible expression in the monumental bronze
statue, designed by the sculptor Ettore Ferrari, a mason and later
Grand Master of the masonic lodge, the Grande Oriente d&rsquo;Italia,
located in Rome. In 1889, in the face of tooth-and-nail opposition
from the Vatican, the statue was erected, glaring directly towards the
Holy See, on the very spot in the Campo dei Fiori where Bruno was
believed to have been burned at the stake. For nineteenth-century
Italian intellectuals such as Vincenzo Gioberti, Bertrando Spaventa
and Francesco Fiorentino, he was, as he had been for Enlightenment
thinkers, a &ldquo;Spinozist&rdquo; in many respects or more broadly,
a secular humanist, someone who had liberated the human spirit from
the suffocating confines of religious orthodoxy and paved the way for
modern philosophy and natural science. Catholic apologists rose to the
Church&rsquo;s defence, belittling this &ldquo;Brunomania&rdquo;, as
they labelled it, and on occasion denying that Bruno had been
executed. Amid the turmoil, Bertrando Spaventa, Felice Tocco,
Francesco Fiorentino and other Italian scholars produced critical
editions of Bruno&rsquo;s Latin and Italian works or wrote studies on
them, thereby laying the foundations of modern Bruno scholarship and
appreciation of him as a philosopher. During the twentieth century
Bruno enjoyed a reputation among orthodox historians of the Soviet
Union as the first modern genius of a materialist philosophy; those
who, like Lev Karsavin, presented a philosophically and historically
contextualized interpretation of his thought, were persecuted for
their &ldquo;bourgeois&rdquo; views. Comparatively recent attempts to
establish magic or mnemotechnics as the key to his philosophy such as
those of Frances Yates, valuable though they remain for their many
incidental details and insights, obscure Bruno&rsquo;s stated
intention to articulate a &ldquo;new philosophy&rdquo;, <em>tout
court</em>.</p>
</div>

